!.Many of the terms still feel unfamiliar to me, but I understand that enabling Windows Explorer integration allows me to access and use Git directly from my file explorer. The one option I clearly recognized was selecting Notepad as my default editor—it’s simple and easy to use, which makes it a good starting point for me.
2.Using the shell is a fast and straightforward way to execute commands with fewer steps. Compared to an IDE like Thonny, which takes longer to open and navigate, the shell feels quicker and more efficient. It also gives you direct interaction with the operating system. I remember using it before to install software, although I can’t recall exactly which one.
3.When I entered the command cd usr/, the shell displayed /usr as the result after I used the pwd command.
4.The file I opened was a Markdown (.md) file. It had three sections: the preview, the code view, and the blame tab. The preview showed my repository’s name and description. The code view displayed the same information in plain text format. The blame tab, as I understand it, shows the history of edits and the users who made them.
